# Kong Rule — Exposure and Route Management

Kong is the platform gateway for deployed agents/apps.

## Route model
Every public deployment route must be derived from persisted deployment metadata.

## Exposure rules
- Public exposure must be explicit, never implicit
- Preview routes and production routes must be distinguishable
- Route generation must be deterministic
- Protected routes must support auth policy assignment

## Gateway resources
Prefer Kubernetes-native route definitions that Kong can reconcile.

## Required route metadata
- route id
- deployment id
- tenant id
- environment
- visibility
- auth mode
- rate limit profile
- hostname/path mapping

## Auth modes
Support these concepts in the domain model:
- public
- api_key
- jwt
- oidc (future-ready)

## Safety
- Never create public wildcard routes by default
- Never expose admin/internal services through Kong
- Enforce explicit allowlists for management endpoints

## Naming
Route names must be stable, readable, and traceable back to deployment records
